If we start with a list like this: 

{code}
1. one
2. CURSOR HERE two
3. three
{code}

And pasted the following list: 

{code}
1. a
2. b
{code}

The result should be: 

{code}
1. one
2. a
3. b 
4. CURSOR HERE two
5. three
{code}

Notice that the list was pasted _before_ the cursor. 

Similarly, if the cursor is _after_ an existing list item, pasting will result in the pasted list coming _after_.

Apologies if this has been already reported. It also probably comes under the existing umbrella issue [CONF-6992]

A user of our WIKI entered the incorrect code for embedding an image into a WIKI page (paramaters should be separated by a comma instead of a pipe):
{code}
!image.jpg|width=100|height=100!
{code}

However, round-tripping causes the {{|height=100}} string to _double_. 
I.e: on the first round trip the markup becomes:
{code}
!image.jpg|width=100|height=100|height=100!
{code}
on the next:
{code}
!image.jpg|width=100|height=100|height=100|height=100|height=100!
{code}
... and so on.

This eventually caused the embed string to balloon to a massive amount, which ended up causing other issues.
While I understand this is incorrect markup, it shouldn't result in massive amount of extra markup to be created.

When using the below macro in Confluence, if you try to edit a page that contains it, the browser freezes and CPU goes to 100%.
{code}
{noformat}
################################################################################
##             TEST - TEST - TEST - TEST - TEST - TEST - TEST - TEST                  
##                                                                            
################################################################################
{noformat}
{code}

WORKAROUND
This issue was not found in Confluence 4.0, so upgrading to this version is a workaround.

Steps to Reproduce:
# Create a new User Macro called 'insidetest' with title 'insidetest'
# Keep the default of 'No Macro Body'.
# Insert the following in the template:
{code}
## @noparams
This is the insidetest macro
{code}
# Save the macro.
# Create another user macro called 'outsidetest' with title 'outsidetest'
# Keep the default of 'No Macro Body'
# Insert the following in the template:
{code}
## @noparams
{insidetest}
This is the outsidetest macro
{code}
# Save the macro.
# Create a new page in some space.
# In the body of the page, insert the 'insidetest' macro.
# On a separate line, insert the 'outsidetest' macro.
# Save the page and view it.

The 'insidetest' macro will render and say:
{code}
This is the insidetest macro
{code}
but the 'outsidetest' macro will render with:
{code}
{outsidetest}This is the outsidetest macro
{code}
instead of:
{code}
This is the insidetest macro
This is the outsidetest macro
{code}
